{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Changed view: use full English in block quote so reversal experiment works",
    "content": "This is a genuinely good argument and it changes my view.\n\nThe author is right: the reversal works only if the reader has something to reverse. The whole point of the passage is that we *start* with a natural, intuitive understanding of these concepts -- and then discover that understanding is upside down. If the reader encounters \"De\" they have no intuitive understanding to overturn. The passage becomes ethnography instead of philosophy.\n\n**Revised position:** Use full English in the block quote: \"the Way, virtue, humaneness, rightness, ritual conduct.\" Let the reader *feel* the familiar hierarchy. Then when the author's analysis dismantles it, the reader experiences the reversal in their own conceptual vocabulary.\n\nThe 德 shift from \"virtue\" to \"(constitutive) character\" now has even more force -- the reader actively felt what \"virtue\" meant, and now watches that meaning get reconstructed as something else entirely.\n\nI was wrong to prioritize terminological consistency over experiential force. The author's own framework (the philosophical experiment, meaning as felt experience) demands that the translation produce *felt understanding* in the reader, not just notational coherence."
  }
}
